# 2. Cryptography {#_computer_systems_security_planning_for_success.xhtml__cryptography}
This chapter is meant to serve as a brief and gentle introduction to the cryptographic concepts often encountered in the

field of security. It is by no means exhaustive but it should provide a basis for a better understanding of why

protocols are designed the way they are. Cryptography is a method of scrambling data into non-readable text. It allows

us to transform data into a secure form so that unauthorized users cannot view it.

:::: {.section .sect2 title="2.1. Why do we need cryptography?"}

